URL_FOR Notes:

In Flask, url_for() builds the URL from:

endpoint name (route)
path params (must match <...> in the route)

anything left over becomes query string (?key=value&...)
So you “stack ’em up,” but there’s one rule:

# Rule

If the route is /foo/<entity_ulid>/bar,
then entity_ulid=... is required and goes into the path.

If the route is /foo/bar,
then entity_ulid=... becomes ?entity_ulid=....

Examples
# Path param route: /resources/onboard/<entity_ulid>/profile
url_for("resources.onboard_profile", entity_ulid=entity_ulid)

# Query string route: /resources/onboard/start?entity_ulid=...
url_for("resources.onboard_start", entity_ulid=entity_ulid)

# Multiple query args:
url_for(
    "resources.onboard_start",
    entity_ulid=entity_ulid,
    reset=1,
    from_wizard="entity",
)

“Make sure they have a place to land”
On the other side, grab them from the right spot:

Path params:
Flask passes into your view function args
(def onboard_profile(entity_ulid): ...)

Query params:
request.args.get("from_wizard")

POST fields:
request.form.get(...)



