Here’s a small terminal redirection cheat sheet you can keep nearby.

## Output redirection

Write normal output to a file, replacing it:
command > file.txt

Append normal output to a file:
command >> file.txt

Discard normal output:
command >/dev/null

## Error redirection

Write errors to a file, replacing it:
command 2> errors.txt

Append errors to a file:
command 2>> errors.txt

Discard errors:
command 2>/dev/null

## Output + errors together

Send both normal output and errors to the same file:
command > all.txt 2>&1

Send both to the trash:
command >/dev/null 2>&1

## Pipes

Send output from one command into another:
command1 | command2

Example:
ls -l | less

## Handy examples
Check JSON syntax without printing the whole file:
python -m json.tool policy.json >/dev/null

Save a directory listing:
ls -l > listing.txt

Save only errors from a command:
pytest 2> pytest_errors.txt

Save everything from a command:
pytest > pytest_run.txt 2>&1

## Easy way to remember it

* `>` = normal output goes somewhere else
* `>>` = append normal output
* `2>` = errors go somewhere else
* `|` = pass output into the next command
* `/dev/null` = discard bucket

## One small caution

Order matters here:
command > file.txt 2>&1

This works the way most people expect.
But changing the order can behave differently.
When in doubt, use that exact form.



